I was just rereading an old Rolling Stone interview with Bob Dylan and he was discussing the importance of understanding the music you want to play. He talks about how he was immersed in a folk culture, he lived at a pivotal time where you could see these big names in folk play live all the time. He then proceeds to say that as our society shifts away from this communal musician enviornment and we are more and more distanced from the music, we lose our connection to it. So basically, when people are trying to write folk songs/love songs, they end up sounding insincere because they are trying too hard to emulate the sound that they basically don't know anything about. In the end, Dylan implies that in order to write a good song that doesn't sound cheesy or cliche that the songwriter should study the old songs and find the secret within those songs. Discover what made the songs sound so authentic when they said "I love you".
There's a special formula for writing songs. You have to tap into that and find the key to it.
